    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_8368371" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/8368371" />
    <a title="Charlotte" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/580517-charlotte"><img alt="Charlotte" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/8368371?book_show_action=true">Oct 28, 2007</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Charlotte" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Charlotte" href="/user/show/580517-charlotte">Charlotte</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer8368371" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17391212115647869021"> I learned how not to treat friends. <br/><br/> I couldn&apos;t believe that Ann didn&apos;t end her friendship with Lucy after so many irritating incidents on Lucy&apos;s part. I would have backed out of sharing an apartment with Lucy if she had jumped up on me when I first arrived at the apartment.<br/><br/> When Lucy demanded that Ann tell her that she (Ann) loved her most, why did Ann cater to her wishes? <br/><br/> The author did not explain to my satisfaction why Lucy continued to have friends. Apparently Lucy must have had some sort</span>
  <span id="freeText17391212115647869021" style="display:none"> I learned how not to treat friends. <br /><br /> I couldn't believe that Ann didn't end her friendship with Lucy after so many irritating incidents on Lucy's part. I would have backed out of sharing an apartment with Lucy if she had jumped up on me when I first arrived at the apartment.<br /><br /> When Lucy demanded that Ann tell her that she (Ann) loved her most, why did Ann cater to her wishes? <br /><br /> The author did not explain to my satisfaction why Lucy continued to have friends. Apparently Lucy must have had some sort of charisma. Surely pity could not have kept her friends hanging around, watching for her to drop crumbs their way. It seemed to me that Lucy just used her friends.<br /><br /> Maybe the answer is in Autobiography of a Face. I have not read that book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17391212115647869021" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


